    # Loop through each row in the df_ dataframe
    for (i in 1:nrow(merge_df)) {
      code <- merge_df[i, 1]
      value <- merge_df[i, 3]

      # Check if the code exists in the data_ dataframe
      if (code %in% colnames(data_df)) {
        # Insert the value at the corresponding column in the new row
        new_row[, code] <- value
      }
    }

    # Add the new row to the data_ dataframe
    data_list[[k]] <- rbind(data_list[[k]], new_row)
  }
}
```
In this modified loop, I separated the handling of multiple entries in B, D, and G dataframes from the others. The `current_entry` variable keeps track of the current entry being processed. If a new entry has started (the starting code is encountered and it's not the first row), it increments `current_entry`, creates a new row and appends it to the corresponding data_ dataframe. Then, it updates the last row of the data_ dataframe with the values from the df_ dataframe.

