It doesn't give me compile errors but I want class A to throw errors if the methods/properties are not implemented in the class.

To enforce the implementation of all methods and properties of the interface in the implementing class, use the "explicit interface implementation" syntax:

interface IA
{
   int Prop { get; }
   void Method();
}

class A : IA
{
   int IA.Prop { get { /* implementation */ } }
   void IA.Method() { /* implementation */ }
}

This way, if any required member of the interface is not implemented in class A, it will result in a compilation error.

